const FAQS = [
  { question: 'How does the AI calculate material quantities?', answer: "The AI uses IS code formulas calibrated against Buildogram's database of completed projects across Chennai. For concrete items, it applies M20/M25 mix designs per IS 456:2000. For masonry, it applies standard fly-ash brick dimensions (230x110x75mm) with mortar joint and wastage factors baked in." },
  { question: 'Are these procurement quantities or BOQ quantities?', answer: 'These are procurement quantities — inclusive of standard wastage factors: 5–10% for cement, 3–5% for steel, and 8–12% for bricks. They are designed to help you plan material orders rather than serve as contract BOQ line items. For formal BOQ, use our AI BOQ Checker.' },
  { question: 'Can I use this for planning material purchases from vendors?', answer: "Absolutely. After getting your estimate, you can use Buildogram's material procurement service to source cement (Ultratech, ACC, Ramco), steel (Kamdhenu, JSPL, SAIL), and other items at negotiated wholesale rates — shipped directly to your construction site in Chennai." },
  { question: 'Does it account for different IS grades?', answer: 'Yes. Select M20 or M25 concrete grade and Fe415/Fe500D steel grade to get grade-appropriate quantity estimates. Higher-grade concrete requires different water:cement ratios which affects cement bag count per cubic metre of concrete placed.' },
];
